lk, England, United Kingdom","Dennington, Suffolk, England":"Dennington, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Hadleigh, Suffolk, England":"Hadleigh, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England"},"nl":{"about 1413–about 1453":"circa 1413–circa 1453","1405–Female":"1405–Overleden","1410–1457":"1410–1457","1413–1453":"1413–1453","1410–1470":"1410–1470","1435–1504":"1435–1504","1385–1440":"1385–1440","1390–1441":"1390–1441","1440":"1440","1385":"1385","1470":"1470","6 Jun 1441":"6 juni 1441","1390":"1390","1435":"1435","1413":"1413","1457":"1457","1410":"1410","about 1413":"circa 1413","1453":"1453","1441":"1441","about 1453":"circa 1453","about 1410":"circa 1410","about 1440":"circa 1440","1504":"1504","1405":"1405","Hadleigh, Cosford, Suffolk, England":"Cosford, Suffolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Dennington, Suffolk, England":"Dennington, Suffolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Hadleigh, Suffolk, England":"Hadleigh, Suffolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England"},"en":{"about 1413–about 1453":"about 1413–about 1453","1405–Female":"1405–Deceased","1410–1457":"1410–1457","1413–1453":"1413–1453","1410–1470":"1410–1470","1435–1504":"1435–1504","1385–1440":"1385–1440","1390–1441":"1390–1441","1440":"1440","1385":"1385","1470":"1470","6 Jun 1441":"6 June 1441","1390":"1390","1435":"1435","1413":"1413","1457":"1457","1410":"1410","about 1413":"about 1413","1453":"1453","1441":"1441","about 1453":"about 1453","about 1410":"about 1410","about 1440":"about 1440","1504":"1504","1405":"1405","Hadleigh, Cosford, Suffolk, England":"Cosford, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Dennington, Suffolk, England":"Dennington, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Hadleigh, Suffolk, England":"Hadleigh, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Francis","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["equivalent of Italian Francesco , originally a vocabulary word meaning ‘French’ or ‘Frenchman’ (Late Latin <i>Franciscus</i>;  compare  Frank  ). This was a nickname given to  St Francis  of Assisi (  1181–1226 ) because of his wealthy father's business connections with France. His baptismal name was  Giovanni . He had a pleasant, ordinary life as a child and young man, but after two serious illnesses, a period of military service, and a year as a prisoner of war in Perugia, he turned from the world and devoted himself to caring for the poor and sick. He was joined by groups of disciples, calling themselves ‘minor friars’ (<i>friari minores</i>). The main features of the Franciscan rule are humility, poverty, and love for all living creatures. The given name occurs occasionally in England as early as  1300 , and more frequently from the early 16th century, when there was a surge of admiration for, and imitation of, Italian Renaissance culture."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Francis Margaret Glemham was born about 1413, in Cosford, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom, her father, John Glemham, was 30 and her mother, Rose Phelip, was 24. She married Captain William Forth about 1460, in Hadleigh, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom. She died about 1453, in her hometown, at the age of 42."},"et":{"about 1413–about 1453":"umbes 1413–umbes 1453","1405–Female":"1405–Surnud","1410–1457":"1410–1457","1413–1453":"1413–1453","1410–1470":"1410–1470","1435–1504":"1435–1504","1385–1440":"1385–1440","1390–1441":"1390–1441","1440":"1440","1385":"1385","1470":"1470","6 Jun 1441":"6. juuni 1441","1390":"1390","1435":"1435","1413":"1413","1457":"1457","1410":"1410","about 1413":"